EXAMPLE 3: Crossing the GenAI Divide and Unlocking Real Value

Generative AI is everywhere. The deployment reality is stark. An MIT report shows that only five percent of pilots create ROI. Ninety five percent fail. This is the GenAI Divide.

Mid sized companies feel the pressure. Budgets are tight. Experiments must lead to outcomes. The advantage is that mid sized firms move faster than global enterprises. The challenge is using that agility to cross the divide.

Why AI Efforts Fail
Memory is the first failure point. Generative AI tools do not retain enterprise context. Each interaction starts from scratch. Employees re enter information. Long prompts try to compensate. None of this scales.

Shadow IT makes this worse. Employees use personal accounts on ChatGPT or Copilot. The tools help with small tasks but cannot handle enterprise workflows with continuity.

The second failure is lack of enterprise understanding. Sales records, policies, and support transcripts exist in silos. AI that cannot connect them cannot deliver value.

The third failure is complexity. Integrations, governance, adoption, and security sink most pilots. The problem is not model capability. The problem is workflow integration and enterprise readiness.

The fourth failure is poor project selection. Many pilots are science projects. They are interesting but disconnected from revenue, cost, or compliance. They die fast.

What Success Requires
Success requires reframing AI. Generative AI is only a small part of the solution. Classifiers and predictors drive reliable enterprise outcomes. They retrain. They provide confidence scoring. They fit enterprise workflows.

Continuous learning is essential. AI must evolve with use. Without learning, the system cannot scale.

Leaders must focus on outcomes. Not demos. Not experiments. Choose workflows tied to measurable ROI. Avoid projects that do not matter.

Where Companies Win
Mid market firms succeed with operational use cases. Back office automation delivers fast ROI. Compliance, finance, testing, and document processing produce real gains.

Krista customer Doc Prep 911 automated intake, document understanding, template generation, and system updates. Human in the loop handled exceptions. Labor dropped by up to ninety five percent. Costs dropped eighty percent. Work accelerated eighty percent.

The Role of Agentic Platforms
The future of AI is an agentic web where systems cooperate. Generative AI alone cannot achieve this. Agentic platforms deliver integration, memory, governance, and orchestration.

Agentic platforms coordinate people, systems, and AI to complete outcomes. They support human escalation. They learn continuously. They connect to enterprise systems. They deliver stable, scalable workflows.

Actions Leaders Should Take
Choose pilots with measurable business impact. Avoid homegrown platforms. Vendors succeed more often because they scale across customers. Empower business leaders to own adoption. Keep pilots small. Demand continuous learning and system integration.

The GenAI Divide is real. Most pilots fail. But the path forward is clear. The time to act is now.

