EXAMPLE 4: Choosing the Right Agentic Platform

AI investment has created an explosion of chatbots, copilots, and small agents. Innovation created sprawl. The outcome is fragmentation, not transformation.

Point Solutions Multiply Problems
Task based tools do not accelerate the business. They help individuals. They do not increase enterprise velocity. Companies collect hundreds of small tools. Each introduces logic, interfaces, and failure points. Complexity rises.

Orchestration Drives Outcomes
Agentic platforms orchestrate outcomes, not tasks. They span departments and systems. They complete multi step processes from start to finish. A title document is only one step. A full outcome includes verification, invoicing, payment confirmation, and downstream notifications.

Integration Must Be End to End
Integration must carry context across the entire workflow. Customer identity, pricing, and document types must stay consistent. Single task connectors cannot achieve this. A platform must integrate across outcomes.

AI Must Improve with Use
Generative AI does not improve over time. Agentic platforms require classifiers and predictors trained on enterprise data. Confidence scoring triggers escalation. Without this, automation either fails or makes silent errors.

Enterprise Controls Must Be Built In
Security controls are not optional. Role based access, audit logs, and deterministic workflows must exist from the start. Most vendors expect customers to build these. Krista ships with them.

AI Flexibility Protects Your Investment
Companies must not lock into one model. A platform must allow hot swapping models as better ones appear. Krista makes this easy.

Six Essential Capabilities
The platform must prove:
End to end outcomes
Conversation driven workflows
Trainable models with confidence scoring
Human in the loop escalation
Enterprise security controls
Compatibility with any model

If a vendor cannot demonstrate all six, they are not agentic.

