EXAMPLE 9: MCP — Hype, Risk, and Enterprise Reality

MCP created hype. Many say it is the future of AI integration. It is important, but enterprises must understand the risks.

What MCP Is
MCP connects LLMs to external tools. It is a universal adapter that lets AI take real action. It uses a host, a client, and a server. The server exposes tools or systems.

The protocol is lightweight. The potential is large.

The Promise
MCP enables composable automation. Models can update records, generate reports, or schedule meetings. It connects AI to live systems.

The Risks
Security is the real issue. MCP servers often expose file systems. Many users install them without reviewing the code. Models sometimes ignore “do not delete” instructions.

This mirrors the ActiveX security failures of the 1990s.

Why Enterprises Should Wait
There is no standard way to deploy MCP securely. The setup is manual. There is no governance for tool invocation or payload validation. Companies cannot roll it out at scale. Employees experiment on their own and leak data.

Use It, But Control It
MCP is an advancement. It increases AI utility. It reduces integration friction.

The tools are immature. The safeguards are minimal. The risk is real.

Do not reject MCP. Do not rush into it. Understand the business case. Control what you connect. The model will act. You are responsible for the outcome.

