EXAMPLE 10: AI Agents — What Lies Beneath

OpenAI announced specialized AI agents costing two thousand to twenty thousand dollars per month. This creates sticker shock. Companies consider building their own. That is risky.

The Build vs Buy Dilemma
Companies assume they can build to save cost. They overlook the hidden complexity. AI needs infrastructure, integration, security, orchestration, and adaptability.

The Reality of Building AI Agents
Siloed AI creates no value. Maintenance demands constant updates. Scalability becomes impossible. Many companies waste time and money before realizing that building is harder than buying.

Hidden Challenges
AI requires data pipelines, integrations, security, and compute. AI agents must work together. Enterprise problems require collaboration across agents. AI needs workflow automation and human oversight.

The Real Costs of DIY
Engineering costs add up. AI engineers, software developers, security teams, and infrastructure all cost real money.

Maintenance costs grow as the business evolves. Retraining, integrating new tools, updating workflows, and supporting users consume resources.

The largest cost is time. DIY AI delays outcomes. Teams get stuck in cycles of fixing and rebuilding.

Why a Platform Approach Wins
A platform provides privacy, security, governance, orchestration, and scalability. Companies deploy agents without starting from scratch.

The Right Strategy
DIY AI drains budgets and timeline. A platform approach accelerates outcomes. Krista provides the required capabilities.

If you want ROI, adopt a platform rather than piece together solutions.

